caption: Nice and decent little jardin/ parc around the Rue de Buzenval neighborhood. Safe, and family and kiddos friendly.

My son really liked this playground, but I've yet to see a single park in Paris with swings. Lots of diverse equipment but it gets repetitive after a while and for a 2 almost 3 year old, most are either too challenging or not challenging enough. The safety standards of the equipment is also questionable. Still one of the better parks I've visited in Paris.
I like coming here with the kids now that the play area has been improved. No more sand everywhere. The equipment is all very nice and different enough that the kids can have fun for a long time.
The park is nice to go with kids or simply enjoy lunch. It's very well organized.

Beautiful park and great playgrounds for the kids. The only downsides are: it's sometimes really crowded, and in the summer there isn't much shade during some hours in the afternoon. Otherwise our favorite.
I love the space. The round playground is perfect for kids from 2 to 10 years old. There are lots of benches and because it is round, you can always find one in the shade.
Such a cute square with the wondrous  sounds of playing children.  Easy to sit on a bench and watch or read. Lovely landscaping.
Peaceful location, minutes away from busy road. Nice for taking a break and let the kids play a bit while catching up with friends or reading

Pretty Parisian square, very clean and well frequented. Nice lawn to relax on. There are plenty of benches in the sun or shade. The play areas for children are brand new. The square was cleaned up during the winter.

Very beautiful family square. Good size square with 3 play areas for very young, young and old. Tables for chess are present on the side of the theater-shaped building. Benches are present everywhere and consoles are set up at a distance from the play areas for greater peace of mind. The central play area is very impressive in terms of size and is a perfect place for children to hang out. Therefore, it is very busy.

Vasque square with trees with several play areas and sports facilities. This square was built in 1936, on part of the old Saint-Mand√© gas factory. It owes its name to the famous tragedian Sarah Bernhardt, whose real name was Rosine Bernard (1844-1923). The obelisk is reminiscent of that of Square Ren√©-Le-Gall (13¬∞), another square typical of the 1930s. Nearly 200 trees, bringing together 50 different species, decorate this garden: cone-shaped yews, Japanese sophoras, ginkgos biloba, cedars, redwoods...
Superb large park which has lots of games for children, as well as a large lawn ideal for picnics. Avoid peak hours as it can be very crowded.
